Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, he was the third to put to the vote a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" scored 28%, 7% of the votes were null votes and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory to the "yes", estimating it to be between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on Sunday night.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly", he had assured, congratulating Ecuadorians who head the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calm, according to the Observer Mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a 444-point text that consolidated the " new socialism " advocated by the President.
The draft Constitution entails increasing the power of the State over the economy, reserved for it the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the Head of State, who can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms each and have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally foresees a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
The 19 abducted people have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been liberated by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them looked good on arrival at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special plane to Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical tests, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the hijackers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown hijackers while enjoying an all-terrain safari in a deserted area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since passed from one zulo to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of the organization of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, carried aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of gunshots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled," the official said.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men of the secret services, of the special forces," he said without going into detail.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrain vehicle aboard which contained the hijackers, of whom he killed six, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also claimed that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by that group.
